{"repo": "pyca/bcrypt", "pull_number": 1031, "instance_id": "pyca__bcrypt-1031", "issue_numbers": [1030], "base_commit": "6e297f29ddceb0dbf843663e9fc3f25b3790ec8e", "patch": "diff --git a/src/_bcrypt/src/lib.rs b/src/_bcrypt/src/lib.rs\nindex 11cdba31..a32797db 100644\n--- a/src/_bcrypt/src/lib.rs\n+++ b/src/_bcrypt/src/lib.rs\n@@ -26,13 +26,12 @@ pub const BASE64_ENGINE: base64::engine::GeneralPurpose = base64::engine::Genera\n );\n \n #[pyo3::pyfunction]\n-#[pyo3(signature = (rounds=None, prefix=None))]\n+#[pyo3(signature = (rounds=12, prefix=None), text_signature = \"(rounds=12, prefix=b'2b')\")]\n fn gensalt<'p>(\n     py: pyo3::Python<'p>,\n-    rounds: Option<u16>,\n+    rounds: u16,\n     prefix: Option<&[u8]>,\n ) -> pyo3::PyResult<pyo3::Bound<'p, pyo3::types::PyBytes>> {\n-    let rounds = rounds.unwrap_or(12);\n     let prefix = prefix.unwrap_or(b\"2b\");\n \n     if prefix != b\"2a\" && prefix != b\"2b\" {\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Incomplete python function signature for `gensalt`\nWith `bcrypt` version 4.0.1, the function signature of `gensalt` correctly indicated the default value of the arguments when inspected programmatically:\n\n```\n>>> import inspect\n>>> import bcrypt\n>>> inspect.signature(bcrypt.gensalt)\n<Signature (rounds: int = 12, prefix: bytes = b'2b') -> bytes>\n```\n\nStarting with version 4.1.0 (and still in the latest version 4.3.0), the function signature does not contain the default values anymore:\n\n```\n>>> import inspect\n>>> import bcrypt\n>>> inspect.signature(bcrypt.gensalt)\n<Signature (rounds=None, prefix=None)>\n```\n\nFrom a quick look at the code, I found that the function has the correct signature in https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/blob/6e297f29ddceb0dbf843663e9fc3f25b3790ec8e/src/bcrypt/__init__.pyi#L1\nbut not in the `pyo3` macro in https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/blob/6e297f29ddceb0dbf843663e9fc3f25b3790ec8e/src/_bcrypt/src/lib.rs#L28-L30\n", "hints_text": "Looks like something we should fix, thanks for reporting. Would you be interested in sending a PR for this?\nWill do, however I don't get how to build and test the project locally.\nHopefully the obvious fix is the only needed change, and github's CI will let me know if I break something \ud83d\ude05\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Looks like something we should fix, thanks for reporting. Would you be interested in sending a PR for this?\nWill do, however I don't get how to build and test the project locally.\nHopefully the obvious fix is the only needed change, and github's CI will let me know if I break something \ud83d\ude05\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/commit/09cfd058d1662f821fbe18a988709a614c9e3917"], "created_at": "2025-06-04T21:45:36Z"}
{"repo": "pyca/bcrypt", "pull_number": 1078, "instance_id": "pyca__bcrypt-1078", "issue_numbers": [1076], "base_commit": "e43f568265df7e1aabbaddccc336dbf3ea675df8", "patch": "diff --git a/README.rst b/README.rst\nindex 8744f9de..12380140 100644\n--- a/README.rst\n+++ b/README.rst\n@@ -51,11 +51,15 @@ While bcrypt remains an acceptable choice for password storage, depending on you\n Changelog\n =========\n \n-Unreleased\n-----------\n+5.0.0\n+-----\n \n * Bumped MSRV to 1.74.\n * Added support for Python 3.14 and free-threaded Python 3.14.\n+* Added support for Windows on ARM.\n+* Passing ``hashpw`` a password longer than 72 bytes now raises a\n+  ``ValueError``. Previously the password was silently truncated, following the\n+  behavior of the original OpenBSD ``bcrypt`` implementation.\n \n 4.3.0\n -----\ndiff --git a/pyproject.toml b/pyproject.toml\nindex fdc15f38..9072eccb 100644\n--- a/pyproject.toml\n+++ b/pyproject.toml\n@@ -11,7 +11,7 @@ build-backend = \"setuptools.build_meta\"\n [project]\n name = \"bcrypt\"\n # When updating this, also update lib.rs\n-version = \"4.3.0\"\n+version = \"5.0.0\"\n authors = [\n     {name = \"The Python Cryptographic Authority developers\", email = \"cryptography-dev@python.org\"}\n ]\ndiff --git a/src/_bcrypt/src/lib.rs b/src/_bcrypt/src/lib.rs\nindex 9c5735e8..ad38fdf9 100644\n--- a/src/_bcrypt/src/lib.rs\n+++ b/src/_bcrypt/src/lib.rs\n@@ -210,7 +210,7 @@ mod _bcrypt {\n         // When updating this, also update pyproject.toml\n         // This isn't named __version__ because passlib treats the existence of\n         // that attribute as proof that we're a different module\n-        m.add(\"__version_ex__\", \"4.3.0\")?;\n+        m.add(\"__version_ex__\", \"5.0.0\")?;\n \n         let author = \"The Python Cryptographic Authority developers\";\n         m.add(\"__author__\", author)?;\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "New release?\nIt'd be nice to have a new release available on PyPI to aid downstream free-threaded Python 3.14 support.\n\nThis came up today for FastAPI: https://github.com/fastapi/fastapi/pull/13946#issuecomment-3328604727\n", "hints_text": "Fine with me, I don't think there's blockers. Paul, what's our release\r\nprocess here?\r\n\r\nOn Wed, Sep 24, 2025 at 12:57\u202fPM Nathan Goldbaum ***@***.***>\r\nwrote:\r\n\r\n> *ngoldbaum* created an issue (pyca/bcrypt#1076)\r\n> <https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/issues/1076>\r\n>\r\n> It'd be nice to have a new release available on PyPI to support\r\n> free-threaded Python 3.14 support.\r\n>\r\n> This came up today for FastAPI: fastapi/fastapi#13946 (comment)\r\n> <https://github.com/fastapi/fastapi/pull/13946#issuecomment-3328604727>\r\n>\r\n> \u2014\r\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\r\n> <https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/issues/1076>, or unsubscribe\r\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/AAAAGBDONBXIXNA2OVNXDOT3ULEPLAVCNFSM6AAAAACHMWPWV6VHI2DSMVQWIX3LMV43ASLTON2WKOZTGQ2TAMRQG4YTENA>\r\n> .\r\n> You are receiving this because you are subscribed to this thread.Message\r\n> ID: ***@***.***>\r\n>\r\n\r\n\r\n-- \r\nAll that is necessary for evil to succeed is for good people to do nothing.\r\n\nWe have the same release automation in bcrypt that we do in\r\npyca/cryptography so we can just run a release whenever we want.\r\n\r\nOn Wed, Sep 24, 2025 at 1:49\u202fPM Alex Gaynor ***@***.***>\r\nwrote:\r\n\r\n> *alex* left a comment (pyca/bcrypt#1076)\r\n> <https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/issues/1076#issuecomment-3330032598>\r\n> Fine with me, I don't think there's blockers. Paul, what's our release\r\n> process here?\r\n>\r\n> On Wed, Sep 24, 2025 at 12:57\u202fPM Nathan Goldbaum ***@***.***>\r\n> wrote:\r\n>\r\n> > *ngoldbaum* created an issue (pyca/bcrypt#1076)\r\n> > <https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/issues/1076>\r\n> >\r\n> > It'd be nice to have a new release available on PyPI to support\r\n> > free-threaded Python 3.14 support.\r\n> >\r\n> > This came up today for FastAPI: fastapi/fastapi#13946 (comment)\r\n> > <https://github.com/fastapi/fastapi/pull/13946#issuecomment-3328604727>\r\n> >\r\n> > \u2014\r\n> > Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\r\n> > <https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/issues/1076>, or unsubscribe\r\n> > <\r\n> https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/AAAAGBDONBXIXNA2OVNXDOT3ULEPLAVCNFSM6AAAAACHMWPWV6VHI2DSMVQWIX3LMV43ASLTON2WKOZTGQ2TAMRQG4YTENA>\r\n>\r\n> > .\r\n> > You are receiving this because you are subscribed to this thread.Message\r\n> > ID: ***@***.***>\r\n> >\r\n>\r\n>\r\n> --\r\n> All that is necessary for evil to succeed is for good people to do\r\n> nothing.\r\n>\r\n> \u2014\r\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\r\n> <https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/issues/1076#issuecomment-3330032598>, or\r\n> unsubscribe\r\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/AABHNV7MZBQ2OI6FFHRIH4T3ULKT5AVCNFSM6AAAAACHMWPWV6VHI2DSMVQWIX3LMV43OSLTON2WKQ3PNVWWK3TUHMZTGMZQGAZTENJZHA>\r\n> .\r\n> You are receiving this because you are subscribed to this thread.Message\r\n> ID: ***@***.***>\r\n>\r\n\nCool, so just a PR bumping the version and then we can tag easily.\n\nWe also need to add to the changelog that we now error loudly for passwords >72 chars.\n\nShould we do 5.0 as a result of that, or 4.4.0?\nProbably just do 5.0.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Fine with me, I don't think there's blockers. Paul, what's our release\r\nprocess here?\r\n\r\nOn Wed, Sep 24, 2025 at 12:57\u202fPM Nathan Goldbaum ***@***.***>\r\nwrote:\r\n\r\n> *ngoldbaum* created an issue (pyca/bcrypt#1076)\r\n> <https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/issues/1076>\r\n>\r\n> It'd be nice to have a new release available on PyPI to support\r\n> free-threaded Python 3.14 support.\r\n>\r\n> This came up today for FastAPI: fastapi/fastapi#13946 (comment)\r\n> <https://github.com/fastapi/fastapi/pull/13946#issuecomment-3328604727>\r\n>\r\n> \u2014\r\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\r\n> <https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/issues/1076>, or unsubscribe\r\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/AAAAGBDONBXIXNA2OVNXDOT3ULEPLAVCNFSM6AAAAACHMWPWV6VHI2DSMVQWIX3LMV43ASLTON2WKOZTGQ2TAMRQG4YTENA>\r\n> .\r\n> You are receiving this because you are subscribed to this thread.Message\r\n> ID: ***@***.***>\r\n>\r\n\r\n\r\n-- \r\nAll that is necessary for evil to succeed is for good people to do nothing.\r\n\nWe have the same release automation in bcrypt that we do in\r\npyca/cryptography so we can just run a release whenever we want.\r\n\r\nOn Wed, Sep 24, 2025 at 1:49\u202fPM Alex Gaynor ***@***.***>\r\nwrote:\r\n\r\n> *alex* left a comment (pyca/bcrypt#1076)\r\n> <https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/issues/1076#issuecomment-3330032598>\r\n> Fine with me, I don't think there's blockers. Paul, what's our release\r\n> process here?\r\n>\r\n> On Wed, Sep 24, 2025 at 12:57\u202fPM Nathan Goldbaum ***@***.***>\r\n> wrote:\r\n>\r\n> > *ngoldbaum* created an issue (pyca/bcrypt#1076)\r\n> > <https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/issues/1076>\r\n> >\r\n> > It'd be nice to have a new release available on PyPI to support\r\n> > free-threaded Python 3.14 support.\r\n> >\r\n> > This came up today for FastAPI: fastapi/fastapi#13946 (comment)\r\n> > <https://github.com/fastapi/fastapi/pull/13946#issuecomment-3328604727>\r\n> >\r\n> > \u2014\r\n> > Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\r\n> > <https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/issues/1076>, or unsubscribe\r\n> > <\r\n> https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/AAAAGBDONBXIXNA2OVNXDOT3ULEPLAVCNFSM6AAAAACHMWPWV6VHI2DSMVQWIX3LMV43ASLTON2WKOZTGQ2TAMRQG4YTENA>\r\n>\r\n> > .\r\n> > You are receiving this because you are subscribed to this thread.Message\r\n> > ID: ***@***.***>\r\n> >\r\n>\r\n>\r\n> --\r\n> All that is necessary for evil to succeed is for good people to do\r\n> nothing.\r\n>\r\n> \u2014\r\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\r\n> <https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/issues/1076#issuecomment-3330032598>, or\r\n> unsubscribe\r\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/AABHNV7MZBQ2OI6FFHRIH4T3ULKT5AVCNFSM6AAAAACHMWPWV6VHI2DSMVQWIX3LMV43OSLTON2WKQ3PNVWWK3TUHMZTGMZQGAZTENJZHA>\r\n> .\r\n> You are receiving this because you are subscribed to this thread.Message\r\n> ID: ***@***.***>\r\n>\r\n\nCool, so just a PR bumping the version and then we can tag easily.\n\nWe also need to add to the changelog that we now error loudly for passwords >72 chars.\n\nShould we do 5.0 as a result of that, or 4.4.0?\nProbably just do 5.0.\nThanks all, this is great! \ud83c\udf89 \n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/pyca/bcrypt/commit/29ce2eac53de3c4f6e67c1e7dd3110a08ddde895"], "created_at": "2025-09-25T17:15:55Z"}
